originalText.text: The Majestic on Central Park West in New York City is a true architectural gem. This historic residential skyscraper stands as a true icon of the city's skyline, with an Art Deco design that reflects the elegance and sophistication of its era. Situated along the prestigious Central Park West, the Majestic offers stunning views of Central Park, one of New York's most cherished green spaces. Dating back to the 1930s, the Majestic has a rich history of housing notable residents and celebrities, making it a sought-after address for decades. Inside, the Majestic maintains an air of timeless elegance, with spacious apartments and luxurious amenities. Its appearances in films and popular culture further enhance its status as a cultural landmark in the city. The Majestic on Central Park West is not just a residence; it's a living piece of New York City's history and a symbol of enduring sophistication. Whether admired from the street or lived in, it's a five-star destination that embodies the city's allure and timeless appeal.

originalText.text:
I lived in the Majestic in 1980 while attending the NY Art Student's League during the year that John Lennon lived there and was killed. Tragic days were to follow with chanting "Give peace a chance"
outside my window for several months. The building is housed by some of the most famous artists and musicians as well as other famous people. Pretty amazing experience to start off my life with...age 22.

originalText.text: I just love the architecture of this building. It can be viewed from Central Park, but it's address is 115 Central Park West. It was built in 1929, and completed in 1931 in an Art Deco style. It is 346 feet tall, and has 31 floors. Like the nearby San Remo apartment block, this structure also has twin towers incorporated into its design. The Majestic's architect was Irwin S. Chanin. The Majestic was designated a New York City Landmark by the New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission in 1988.

originalText.text: The Majestic (or Majestic Apartments) is a twin-towered skyscraper housing cooperative located at 115 Central Park West between 71st Street and 72nd Street in Manhattan, New York City. The steel framed building was constructed in 1930–1931 and designed in the Art Deco style by architect and real estate developer Irwin S. Chanin with the assistance of his French associate, Jacques Delamarre.[1] The futuristic sculptures on the building's facade are by Rene Chambellan.
